ssert their independence. By 1950 the nationalist period had begun, a period marked by rapid growth of primary and secondary schools and teacher-training colleges and, most importantly, by a shift in power from the Mission Council to the Synod, which represented the church as a whole. By 1960 the church was back where it had started—with its affairs regulated by a court in which missionaries and natives sat and argued as equals. A former president of the American Historical Association observed more than fifteen years ago that "mission history is a great and underused research laboratory for the comparative observation of cultural stimulus and response in both directions." In God and Maxim Guns, Geoffrey Johnston makes a substantial contribution to the field of mission history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPresbyterian Church of NigeriaxHistory. 0aPresbyterian ChurchxHistoryxNigeria. 0aPresbyterian ChurchxMissionsxHistoryxNigeria. 0aPresbyterian ChurchxMissionszNigeriaxHistory. 0aPresbyterian ChurchzNigeriaxHistory. 0aReligion. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Presbyterian.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920754740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889207547423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889207547/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles